        "step": 7,
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Perfect! ✅ **Circuit created successfully.**\n\n## Wiring Table\n\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| D2 | 7-segment (via 220Ω R_a) | Segment A |\n| D3 | 7-segment (via 220Ω R_b) | Segment B |\n| D4 | 7-segment (via 220Ω R_c) | Segment C |\n| D5 | 7-segment (via 220Ω R_d) | Segment D |\n| D6 | 7-segment (via 220Ω R_e) | Segment E |\n| D7 | 7-segment (via 220Ω R_f) | Segment F |\n| D8 | 7-segment (via 220Ω R_g) | Segment G |\n| D9 | Button A | Increment button (INPUT_PULLUP) |\n| GND | Button B | Ground (button return) |\n| GND | 7-segment GND | Common cathode ground |\n\n## Sketch Summary\n\nThe sketch initializes all 7 segment pins (D2–D8) as outputs and the button (D9) as INPUT_PULLUP. Each button press increments the counter from 0–9, then wraps to 0. The `displayDigit()` function uses a lookup table to set the correct segment pattern for each digit. Each segment resistor limits current to ~20 mA per segment (safe for the Uno).\n\n**How to use:** Press the button to increment the counter. The 7-segment display updates immediately and cycles 0→1→...→9→0."
